g two complete sets of unpaired chromosomes","Cells that undergo meiosis II only","Diploid stem cells located on the basement membrane"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpermatogonia\u003C/strong\u003E are diploid stem cells located along the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules. They undergo mitotic division both to maintain the stem cell population, and give rise to primary spermatocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaploid cells that develop into spermatids\u003C/strong\u003E describes secondary spermatocytes. \u003Cstrong\u003ECells that undergo meiosis II only\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as spermatogonia undergo mitosis, the resultant primary spermatocytes will then undergo meiosis. \u003Cstrong\u003EElongated cells with condensed nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E describes spermatids during spermiogenesis. \u003Cstrong\u003ECells containing two complete sets of unpaired chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E describes primary spermatocytes during prophase I of meiosis. Spermatogonia are diploid and thus contain two complete sets of paired chromosomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spermatogonia are diploid stem cells located along the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules that initiate spermatogenesis","Spermatogonia undergo mitotic division to maintain the stem cell population and produce primary spermatocytes"],"references":["Griswold MD. Spermatogenesis: The Commitment to Meiosis. Physiol Rev. 2016 Jan;96(1):1-17. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00013.2015. PMID: 26537427; PMCID: PMC4698398.","Holstein AF, Schulze W, Davidoff M. Understanding spermatogenesis is a prerequisite for treatment. Reprod Biol Endocrinol. 2003 Nov 14;1:107. doi: 10.1186/1477-7827-1-107. PMID: 14617369; PMCID: PMC293421.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Repro